'Quercus velutina', commonly known as the Black Oak, is a deciduous tree native to North America. It stands tall at an average height of 20-25 meters and has a broad, spreading crown with a diameter of up to 18 meters. Its bark is dark brown to black in color, thick, rugged, and deeply furrowed. The leaves of the Black Oak are lobed, with a distinct U-shape, and are glossy green on the upper surface, turning yellow to orange-red in the fall. The tree produces acorns that are a valuable food source for a variety of wildlife. 'Quercus velutina' can be found growing in a range of habitats, including upland forests, dry ridges, and rocky slopes, and is particularly common in the eastern United States. The wood of this oak tree is used for a variety of purposes, including construction, furniture, and fuel.
